						               													<description>From BoardgameNews.com:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;Igor: The Life of the Party, from newcomers Dug Steen and Nate Beeler, blends a trick-taking game with some of the rules craziness of Fr&amp;eacute;d&amp;eacute;ric Leygonie and Sylvie Barc&amp;rsquo;s Elixir.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;The trick-taking element of Igor: The Life of the Party works mostly as you&amp;rsquo;d expect. Players are dealt a hand of cards, which come in five suits numbered 0-9, and each turn they play one card to the table, following suit if possible. If all the cards played are in suit, the player of the highest numbered card wins; if one or more cards are out of suit, however, then the highest one of those cards wins. The trick&amp;rsquo;s winner scores three coins, and the player with the most coins at the end of the game, which lasts several hands, wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;What makes the game tricky are the rule cards, two of which are in play at the start of the game &amp;ndash; make that in play face-down, which means you have to remember what the rules are throughout the hand. Sample rules are 'When you play a card that has an Igor on it, you must say &amp;quot;Yes, Master&amp;quot;' and 'When you laugh, you must follow your laugh with a &amp;quot;Meow.&amp;quot;' At the start of each turn, the dealer can add or remove one rule from play, and the player who wins the most tricks in a hand has the same option, so rules are constantly popping in and out of the game.&amp;quot;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
